<subSubSection type="discussion">
<paragraph pageNumber="2">
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:BD08FA7B-788B-4285-9548-0F120F97465D" class="Actinopterygii" family="Rivulidae" genus="Simpsonichthys" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Simpsonichthys Carvalho 1959:2" order="Cyprinodontiformes" pageNumber="2" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Simpsonichthys Carvalho</taxonomicName>
is the most diverse genus of Neotropical annual killifishes, comprising 40 valid species, all inhabiting seasonal pools in central and northeastern South America. Monophyly of 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:BD08FA7B-788B-4285-9548-0F120F97465D" class="Actinopterygii" family="Rivulidae" genus="Simpsonichthys" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Simpsonichthys Carvalho 1959:2" order="Cyprinodontiformes" pageNumber="2" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Simpsonichthys</taxonomicName>
and intrageneric species assemblages have been defined in recent phylogenetic studies (e. g., Costa, 2003). Among these assemblages, the clade herein termed 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Rivulidae" genus="Simpsonichthys" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cyprinodontiformes" pageNumber="2" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="notatus">Simpsonichthys notatus species group</taxonomicName>
comprises 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Rivulidae" genus="Simpsonichthys" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cyprinodontiformes" pageNumber="2" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="notatus">S. notatus (Costa &amp; Brasil)</taxonomicName>
, from the upper Rio Tocantins basin, and 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Rivulidae" genus="Simpsonichthys" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cyprinodontiformes" pageNumber="2" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="stellatus">S. stellatus (Costa &amp; Brasil)</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:18CCA4BB-6D66-4288-8A7E-DDDCE377B762" class="Actinopterygii" family="Rivulidae" genus="Simpsonichthys" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Simpsonichthys rufus Costa, Nielsen &amp; de Luca 2001:29" order="Cyprinodontiformes" pageNumber="2" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="rufus">S. rufus Costa &amp; Nielsen</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:2D6458F5-F74B-44D9-AEAE-99DBA1177C83" class="Actinopterygii" family="Rivulidae" genus="Simpsonichthys" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Simpsonichthys similis Costa &amp; Hellner 1999:90" order="Cyprinodontiformes" pageNumber="2" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="similis">S. similis Costa &amp; Hellner</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Rivulidae" genus="Simpsonichthys" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cyprinodontiformes" pageNumber="2" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="trilineatus">S. trilineatus Costa &amp; Brasil</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:F7F23E1E-43B7-4C5B-8867-BDFBF5675CD4" class="Actinopterygii" family="Rivulidae" genus="Simpsonichthys" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Simpsonichthys auratus Costa &amp; Nielsen 2000:8" order="Cyprinodontiformes" pageNumber="2" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="auratus">S. auratus Costa &amp; Nielsen</taxonomicName>
, from the middle Rio 
<normalizedToken originalValue="São">Sao</normalizedToken>
Francisco basin, and 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:C2C14E47-3B21-4111-9EAC-E384DDD527DF" class="Actinopterygii" family="Rivulidae" genus="Simpsonichthys" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Simpsonichthys ocellatus Costa, Nielsen &amp; de Luca 2001:25" order="Cyprinodontiformes" pageNumber="2" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="ocellatus">S. ocellatus Costa, Nielsen &amp; De Luca</taxonomicName>
, from the Rio Jequitinhonha basin. It is diagnosed by a unique frontal squamation pattern, in which the A-scale has all margins free (Costa, 2003). A new species of this clade, collected in a temporary pool associated to the headwaters of the Rio 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Crixás">Crixas</normalizedToken>
, upper Rio Tocantins basin, central Brazil, is described.
</paragraph>
